table-1303-581.caption: Features
data: "Description" and "tags" fields of bookmarks provide this
Can annotate PDF, ODF, .doc, .docx, images, as well as web pages (but only a limited number in the free version)
Includes social features, following, and a social feed of notes. Unlimited and free bookmarking, annotating, and collaboration. Private use allowed.
Currently available as a Google Chrome extension. Allows its users to have a discussion, and vote on each others comments.
1000 character limit per page per user
Public annotations are only allowed for established users. Group tag dictionary feature to encourage tagging consistently within a group.
Allows annotate web site and stores the quote on the cloud server.
Emacs-based; requires technical knowledge to set up; not as user-friendly as some other solutions; non-Latin characters allowed in notes but not in tags

More of a semantic linkage plugin than an annotation service, but it allows public comments and tags to be associated with rebuttal links. Rebutted pages display alerts which link to the rebutting pages with the comment that connects them.

Not primarily a web annotation site - public reddits (sections of the site) are mainly intended for new and/or interesting links, but private reddits can be used for anything. Voting up and down for links; links ranked by #votes and age; thumbnails for images and videos in list of links

Compatible with Firefox, IE, Safari & Chrome. Websites can integrate a version of the tool directly into their sites. Allows replies for threaded discussions. Social network integration for sharing & signing in.
Caches a copy of the entire page to personal library along with annotations.

Annotations are XML-based. Available in HTML5 Viewer for Java and .NET as well as in our Viewing and Conversion SDK for Java, .NET, and Windows. Annotate any format supported including PDF, TIFF, Word, AFP, Excel, JPEG, TXT, HTML, and many more.
Blogs subscribed via Stickis will appear as annotations when they link to the current page. Any web content, including YouTube videos, can be inserted into a note.
Can also annotate PDF documents (but not in the free version). Highlighted PDFs and web pages can be shared with others, who do not need to install anything to view them.

data: The very first published version (sort of preview) of the in-memory OLAP server; MDX/XMLA support are the primary objectives.
Building on the feedback of the community this is the first features complete (e.g., MDX, write back, ...) version. A community (free) version.
Listening on the community, v1.3 continues to expand on the MDX support and offers stronger cube modeling features; worth noticing this is the first version of the visualization library (GVI).
An important step for icCube as this is the first Enterprise ready (vs Community) edition.
Due to the increasing demand for an icCube native reporting, this is the first version featuring the Web Reporting server.
An important step in term of performances and MDX/OLAP features bringing the first generation MDX/OLAP engine to its limit.
Featuring a second generation calculation engine, v4 is the most matured edition of the icCube OLAP server and is making real-time / operational BI a reality.
